{
  "text": "Abdominal pain is the consequence of a distended abdomen caused by air leakage through the perforation site and/or peritonitis caused by fecal spillage into the abdominal cavity. Both a distended abdomen and peritonitis may make it difficult to resume normal oral intake, which extends the NPO duration. A long duration of antibiotics is also needed to control peritonitis. The endoscopist was a consistent risk factor influencing all clinical outcome variables. It is well-known that management and prognosis vary according to the physician in charge in various medical fields, such as cardiology, rheumatology, and gastroenterology. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Endoscopists' skill, knowledge, and experience may affect their decision regarding when to resume oral intake and how long to continue the duration of NPO and hospital stay.",
